{"title_page": "Gwen Fenton", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Gwen Fenton\n| image             = Gwen Fenton.jpg\n| birth_name        = \n| nationality       = Australian\n| fields            = Biology\n| workplaces        = [[Australian Antarctic Division]]\n| alma_mater        = [[University of Tasmania]]\n| known_for         = First female Chief Scientist of the Australian Antarctic Division\n}}\n\n'''Gwen Fenton''' is Chief Scientist of the [[Australian Antarctic Division]] and is the first woman to hold this position.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-12-11/dr-gwen-fenton-becomes-aads-first-female-chief-scientist/7022536|title=Gwen Fenton becomes AAD's first female chief scientist|date=2015-12-11|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2016-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.antarctica.gov.au/news/2015/antarctic-division-appoints-first-female-chief-scientist|title=Antarctic Division appoints first female Chief Scientist|last=|first=|date=|website=antarctica.gov.au|publisher=Australian Antarctic Division|language=en-au|access-date=2016-08-05}}</ref>  She discovered that the fish species [[Orange roughy|''Hoplostethus atlanticus'']] can live to over 100 years old, leading to significant changes to the management of the species.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.antarctica.gov.au/magazine/2016-2020/issue-30-june-2016/people/career-challenges-shape-new-chief-scientist|title=Career challenges shape new Chief Scientist|website=www.antarctica.gov.au|language=en-au|access-date=2016-08-05}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nFenton grew up in Australia, the daughter of two scientists. Her mother was a zoologist and her father was a cosmic ray and aurora physicist who worked with the Australian Antarctic Division during the 1950s.<ref name=\":1\" /> She completed a science degree with Honours at the [[University of Tasmania]] on coastal krill from south-eastern Australia and southern New Zealand. She continued her work at the University of Tasmania as part of a PhD focused on [[mysid|mysid crustaceans]], discovering three new genera and 12 new species, graduating in 1986 at the age of 24.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eprints.utas.edu.au/19936/7/whole_FentonGwenElizabeth1985_thesis_ex_pub_mat.pdf|title=Ecology and taxonomy of mysids (mysidacea : crustacea)|last=|first=|date=1985|website=|publisher=University of Tasmania|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Career and impact==\nFenton's post-doctoral work at the University of Tasmania resulted in the development of a technique to age fish based on the radioactive decay of radium-226 to lead-210.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://frdc.com.au/knowledge/seafood_marketing/Documents/FRDC_Rep_92_41_Fenton.pdf|title=Age determination of oreo dory species by radiometric analysis|last=|first=|date=1996|website=frdc.com.au/|publisher=University of Tasmania|access-date=}}</ref> This revolutionized the understanding of the age of the important fishery species, orange roughy. Her work revealed that this species is extremely slow-growing, not maturing until between 20 and 25 years of age, with significant implications for sustainable management of catch limits for the species.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ecosmagazine.com/?act=view_file&file_id=EC68p13.pdf|title=Methuselah of the deep|last=|first=|date=1991|website=ecosmagazine.com|publisher=Ecos|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFenton joined the Tasmanian Government in marine environmental management and policy development in 1996. In her role she developed environmental monitoring programs for Tasmanian salmon farms, developed ballast water policy and provided  advice on marine infrastructure developments.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2003 she joined the Australian Antarctic Division as the Manager of Science Planning and Coordination.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2015  Fenton became the first female Chief Scientist of the Australian Antarctic Division.<ref name=\":0\" /> Her role includes reviewing the Antarctic Science Strategic Plan and strengthening collaborations with East Antarctic partners such as China, India, Japan and France. She will also be working to ensure that the science program is ready to take advantage of the expanded capability that will come with the launch of Australia's new [[icebreaker]] in 2020.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.antarctica.gov.au/science/meet-our-scientists/dr-gwen-fenton Gwen Fenton] at the [[Australian Antarctic Division]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fenton, Gwen}}\n[[Category:Australian women scientists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Antarctic scientists]]\n[[Category:Women Antarctic scientists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Gwen Fenton\n| image             = Gwen Fenton.jpg\n| birth_name        = \n| nationality       = Australian\n| fields            = Biology\n| workplaces        = [[Australian Antarctic Division]]\n| alma_mater        = [[University of Tasmania]]\n| known_for         = First female Chief Scientist of the Australian Antarctic Division\n}}\n\n'''Gwen Fenton''' is Chief Scientist of the [[Australian Antarctic Division]] and is the first woman to hold this position.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-12-11/dr-gwen-fenton-becomes-aads-first-female-chief-scientist/7022536|title=Gwen Fenton becomes AAD's first female chief scientist|date=2015-12-11|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2016-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.antarctica.gov.au/news/2015/antarctic-division-appoints-first-female-chief-scientist|title=Antarctic Division appoints first female Chief Scientist|last=|first=|date=|website=antarctica.gov.au|publisher=Australian Antarctic Division|language=en-au|access-date=2016-08-05}}</ref>  She discovered that the fish species [[Orange roughy|''Hoplostethus atlanticus'']] can live to over 100 years old, leading to significant changes to the management of the species.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.antarctica.gov.au/magazine/2016-2020/issue-30-june-2016/people/career-challenges-shape-new-chief-scientist|title=Career challenges shape new Chief Scientist|website=www.antarctica.gov.au|language=en-au|access-date=2016-08-05}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nFenton grew up in Australia, the daughter of two scientists. Her mother was a zoologist and her father was a cosmic ray and aurora physicist who worked with the Australian Antarctic Division during the 1950s.<ref name=\":1\" /> She completed a science degree with Honours at the [[University of Tasmania]] on coastal krill from south-eastern Australia and southern New Zealand. She continued her work at the University of Tasmania as part of a PhD focused on [[mysid|mysid crustaceans]], discovering three new genera and 12 new species, graduating in 1986 at the age of 24.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eprints.utas.edu.au/19936/7/whole_FentonGwenElizabeth1985_thesis_ex_pub_mat.pdf|title=Ecology and taxonomy of mysids (mysidacea : crustacea)|last=|first=|date=1985|website=|publisher=University of Tasmania|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Career and impact==\nFenton's post-doctoral work at the University of Tasmania resulted in the development of a technique to age fish based on the radioactive decay of radium-226 to lead-210.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://frdc.com.au/knowledge/seafood_marketing/Documents/FRDC_Rep_92_41_Fenton.pdf|title=Age determination of oreo dory species by radiometric analysis|last=|first=|date=1996|website=frdc.com.au/|publisher=University of Tasmania|access-date=}}</ref> This revolutionized the understanding of the age of the important fishery species, orange roughy. Her work revealed that this species is extremely slow-growing, not maturing until between 20 and 25 years of age, with significant implications for sustainable management of catch limits for the species.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ecosmagazine.com/?act=view_file&file_id=EC68p13.pdf|title=Methuselah of the deep|last=|first=|date=1991|website=ecosmagazine.com|publisher=Ecos|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFenton joined the Tasmanian Government in marine environmental management and policy development in 1996. In her role she developed environmental monitoring programs for Tasmanian salmon farms, developed ballast water policy and provided  advice on marine infrastructure developments.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2003 she joined the Australian Antarctic Division as the Manager of Science Planning and Coordination.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2015  Fenton became the first female Chief Scientist of the Australian Antarctic Division.<ref name=\":0\" /> Her role includes reviewing the Antarctic Science Strategic Plan and strengthening collaborations with East Antarctic partners such as China, India, Japan and France. She will also be working to ensure that the science program is ready to take advantage of the expanded capability that will come with the launch of Australia's new [[icebreaker]] in 2020.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.antarctica.gov.au/science/meet-our-scientists/dr-gwen-fenton Gwen Fenton] at the [[Australian Antarctic Division]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n<!-- Categories for this template, but not the final article -->\n\n<!-- Categories for the final article, but not this template -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fenton, Gwen}}\n[[Category:Australian women scientists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Antarctic scientists]]\n[[Category:Women Antarctic scientists]]\n", "name_user": "Kj cheetham", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gwen_Fenton"}
